[6] Kansas and Missouri
Date: Tue 1 May 2018
Source: News-Press Now [edited]
http://www.newspressnow.com/news/local_news/measles-outbreaks-hit-close-to-home/article_799b2772-217a-5c13-b8b1-a63b8c7a638c.html


Numerous outbreaks of the measles are spreading throughout parts of Kansas and Missouri. There have been 18 reported cases in Johnson County, Kansas, and surrounding counties. Handwashing and covering one's mouth aren't just important manners to practice, they are becoming essential to preventing the spread of deadly disease.

In Missouri, Liberty Middle School has prohibited 13 unvaccinated students from attending classes after the school was exposed to an outbreak on [18 Apr 2018]. The 13 students are the only ones out of 791 students to not receive the measles-mumps-rubella vaccine for religious or medical exemptions.

Dr. Cynthia Brownfield is a physician at Mosaic Life Care and she said since the outbreaks are close enough to the area that residents should be aware. "It's not that far away. It's only one hour away. But most viruses and most outbreaks are just a plane ride away as well," Brownfield said.

Brownfield added the disease is incredibly contagious and can be transmitted by a simple cough. The disease can stay in the air for up to 2 hours. "Measles is probably the most contagious virus that we know," Brownfield said.

She said since many people nowadays are unfamiliar with older diseases such as measles, they don't take the threat as seriously. "People get a very false sense of security," Brownfield said. "We don't see measles that often but measles is a serious illness."

According to Brownfield, the symptoms that often accompany the disease is an unsightly rash, high fever, deafness and even pneumonia. Brownfield said pneumonia is often the deadliest side effect of the measles.

But why is the disease spreading so quickly in this day and age? Brownfield thinks some of it has to do with people consuming false information about vaccines.

"Don't trust social media," Brownfield said. "The amount of Facebook posts that I see that are incorrect, or have false information is staggering. Somehow they're played off that it's on social media so it's actually the truth, but it's not."

Brownfield said she recommends everyone who is old enough and medically able to should receive the measles vaccine. But if your child is medically exempt from receiving the vaccine, Brownfield said parents must be more vigilant.

"Make sure that you're smart with where you're taking your child that's too young to be vaccinated and just keeping your radar up. These things can occur," she said.

[Byline: Zach Barrett]

